title: LATERALUS Architecture Overview
subtitle: How Everything Fits Together
---

# Architecture

LATERALUS is a multi-target language with a modular compiler architecture.
This document explains how the pieces connect.

## Compilation Pipeline

```
Source Code (.ltl)
    |
    v
[Lexer] -- Tokenization (123 token types)
    |
    v
[Parser] -- Recursive descent, 1756 lines
    |       -- 106 AST node types
    v
[AST] -- Abstract Syntax Tree
    |
    +--- [Type Checker] (v1.5: Hindley-Milner TypeInferencer)
    |         |-- TypeVar generation (fresh_typevar)
    |         |-- Constraint collection (constrain)
    |         |-- Unification (occurs_check + unify)
    |         |-- Substitution (substitute + solve)
    |         |-- Pattern binding inference (infer_pattern)
    |
    +--- [Optimizer] -- O0-O3 optimization levels
    |         |-- Constant folding
    |         |-- Dead code elimination
    |         |-- Strength reduction
    |         |-- Common subexpression elimination
    |         |-- Pipeline fusion
    |         |-- Dead branch elimination (v2.4)
    |         |-- Algebraic simplification — 20 identities (v2.4)
    |         |-- Function inlining analysis (v2.4)
    |
    v
[Code Generator] -- Target selection (7 backends)
    |
    +--- [Python Target] -- Transpile to Python 3.10+
    |         |
    |         v
    |    [Subprocess] -- Execute generated Python
    |
    +--- [C Target] -- Transpile to C99 (hosted or freestanding)
    |
    +--- [JS Target] -- Transpile to JavaScript (ES2020)
    |
    +--- [WASM Target] -- Transpile to WebAssembly text format
    |
    +--- [IR Target] -- Three-address intermediate representation
    |         |
    |         v
    |    [VM] -- 102 opcode virtual machine
    |
    +--- [Binary Target] -- Compile to .ltlc
    |         |
    |         v
    |    [LTLC Format] -- Proprietary binary with sections
    |
    +--- [Disassembler] -- Round-trip bytecode disassembly (v2.4)
```

## Engine Architecture

```
lateralus_lang/
    engines.py          -- Unified engine interface (lazy loading)
    |
    +--- math_engine.py     -- LTLNumber, Matrix, Vector, Interval, Dual
    +--- crypto_engine.py   -- SHA/BLAKE2b/HMAC, AES-GCM, LBE encoding
    +--- science.py         -- Constants, dimensions, ODE, FFT
    +--- markup.py          -- LTLML parser and HTML renderer
    +--- bytecode_format.py -- .ltlc compiler/decompiler
    +--- error_engine.py    -- Rich diagnostics with suggestions
```

Each engine exposes a `*_BUILTINS` dictionary that maps function names
to Python callables. The `engines.py` module unifies them via
`get_all_builtins()` for injection into the runtime preamble.

## Type System

```
TypeKind (14 variants)
    |
    +--- PrimitiveType (int, float, str, bool, none)
    +--- FunctionType (params -> return_type)
    +--- ListType, MapType, TupleType
    +--- UnionType (A | B)
    +--- OptionalType (T?)
    +--- TypeVar (generic placeholder)
    +--- StructType (named fields)
    +--- InterfaceType (method signatures)
    +--- AnyType (escape hatch)
```

The type checker runs as an optional pass before code generation.
Type annotations use the syntax `name: Type` and `-> ReturnType`.

## v1.5 Hindley-Milner Inference

The `TypeInferencer` (in `type_system.py`) implements a constraint-based
subset of the Hindley-Milner algorithm:

```
Phase 1 — Constraint Collection
    For each expression node, call inferencer.constrain(T_expected, T_actual).
    Fresh type variables are created with fresh_typevar("T").

Phase 2 — Solving
    inferencer.solve() iterates over all (T1, T2, context) triples.
    Each pair is unified via the unify(t1, t2) method.

Phase 3 — Substitution
    After solving, substitute(typ) applies the final substitution map
    to resolve all remaining TypeVars to concrete types.
```

### Robinson Unification Rules (unify)

| Case | Rule |
|------|------|
| `T == T` | trivially succeed |
| `T == ANY` or `ANY == T` | succeed (ANY is top type) |
| `α` (TypeVar) ~ `T` | bind α → T (if no occurs-check failure) |
| `T` ~ `α` (TypeVar) | bind α → T |
| `List<A>` ~ `List<B>` | unify(A, B) |
| `Map<K1,V1>` ~ `Map<K2,V2>` | unify(K1,K2) and unify(V1,V2) |
| `(A1,...)->R1` ~ `(B1,...)->R2` | unify each param pair; unify returns |
| `T?` ~ `U?` | unify(T, U) |
| `T?` ~ `U` | unify(T, U) (nullable coercion) |

### Pattern Inference (infer_pattern)

Match arm patterns bind new variables. `infer_pattern(pattern, subject)` returns
`{name: LTLType}` bindings for every captured name:

```
WildcardPattern(_)            → {}
LiteralPattern(42)            → {}  (adds constraint: subject == int)
BindingPattern(x)             → {x: resolve(subject)}
TypePattern(Point, [px, py])  → {px: T0, py: T1}
EnumVariantPattern(Result::Ok, [v]) → {v: V0}
TuplePattern((a, b))          → {a: T0, b: T1}  (adds subject == Tuple<T0,T1>)
ListPattern([head, ...tail])  → {head: E, tail: List<E>}
OrPattern(p1 | p2)            → intersection of bindings from p1 and p2
```

## VM Opcode Reference

The stack-based VM (`lateralus_lang/vm/vm.py`) uses 102 opcodes:

### Stack Operations
| Opcode | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| `PUSH_INT n` | push integer constant |
| `PUSH_FLOAT f` | push float constant |
| `PUSH_STR s` | push string constant |
| `PUSH_BOOL b` | push boolean |
| `PUSH_NIL` | push nil |
| `POP` | discard top of stack |
| `DUP` | duplicate top of stack |
| `SWAP` | swap top two items |

### Arithmetic
| Opcode | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| `ADD`, `SUB`, `MUL`, `DIV` | binary arithmetic |
| `MOD`, `POW` | modulo, exponent |
| `NEG` | negate top |
| `FLOOR_DIV` | integer division |

### Comparisons & Logic
| Opcode | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| `EQ`, `NEQ` | equality |
| `LT`, `GT`, `LTE`, `GTE` | ordered comparison |
| `AND`, `OR`, `NOT` | boolean logic |

### Control Flow
| Opcode | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| `JUMP offset` | unconditional jump |
| `JUMP_IF_FALSE offset` | pop, jump if false |
| `JUMP_IF_TRUE offset` | pop, jump if true |
| `CALL name nargs` | call function |
| `RETURN` | return from function |
| `YIELD val` | suspend generator |

### Containers
| Opcode | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| `BUILD_LIST n` | pop n items → list |
| `BUILD_MAP n` | pop 2n items → map |
| `BUILD_TUPLE n` | pop n items → tuple |
| `INDEX` | list/map subscript |
| `FIELD name` | field access |
| `STORE_INDEX` | list/map assignment |

### Scoping
| Opcode | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| `LOAD_LOCAL name` | push local variable |
| `STORE_LOCAL name` | pop → local variable |
| `LOAD_GLOBAL name` | push global |
| `STORE_GLOBAL name` | pop → global |

### Pipeline
| Opcode | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| `PIPELINE` | invoke the piped function |
| `PIPELINE_OPT` | `\|?` — skip if nil |
| `PROPAGATE` | `?` — propagate error/nil upward |

## IR (Three-Address) Representation

The `ir.py` module produces a flat list of `IRInstr` objects:

```
IRInstr(op="ASSIGN", dest="t0", left="x", right=None)
IRInstr(op="ADD", dest="t1", left="t0", right="1")
IRInstr(op="CALL", dest="t2", left="println", right=["t1"])
IRInstr(op="JUMP_IF", dest=None, left="t2", right="label_12")
IRInstr(op="LABEL", dest="label_12", left=None, right=None)
```

The IR is used as the input to the bytecode compiler and as the basis for
optimization passes (constant folding reads IR nodes directly).

## Integration Points

The `integration_patch.py` module connects new engines to the
existing compiler without modifying original files:

1. `patch_builtins()` -- Injects engine functions into codegen preamble
2. `patch_cli()` -- Registers new CLI subcommands
3. `patch_error_handling()` -- Enhances error messages
4. `patch_compiler()` -- Adds optimizer passes

Call `apply_all()` at startup to activate all patches.

## Developer Tools Architecture

```
Developer Tools
    |
    +--- LSP Server (lsp_server.py)
    |       -- JSON-RPC 2.0, completions, hover, diagnostics
    |
    +--- Formatter (formatter.py)
    |       -- Whitespace, indentation, pipeline alignment
    |
    +--- Linter (linter.py)
    |       -- 21+ rules, suggestions, strict mode
    |
    +--- Debugger (debugger.py)
    |       -- Breakpoints, stepping, watches, REPL
    |
    +--- DAP Server (dap_server.py)
    |       -- Debug Adapter Protocol (VS Code debug integration)
    |
    +--- Package Manager (package_manager.py)
    |       -- lateralus.json, dependency resolution, scaffolding
    |
    +--- Test Runner (test_runner.py)
    |       -- Discover @test functions, run, report
    |
    +--- Benchmark Suite (bench.py)
    |       -- Per-engine benchmarks, statistics, JSON output
    |
    +--- Watch Mode (watch.py)
            -- File watcher for incremental compilation
```

## File Format Reference

### Source (.ltl)
Plain text, UTF-8 encoded LATERALUS source code.

### Compiled Binary (.ltlc)
```
Magic:    \x89LTL (4 bytes)
Version:  2 bytes (major.minor)
Flags:    4 bytes
Sections:
    HEADER   -- Metadata, timestamps
    CODE     -- Compressed bytecode (zlib)
    DATA     -- String/number constants
    SYMBOLS  -- Symbol table
    TYPES    -- Type information (v1.5: includes HM type variables)
    DEBUG    -- Source maps, line info
    META     -- Custom metadata
Footer:
    HMAC-SHA256 integrity signature
```

### Markup (.ltlml)
```
---
frontmatter: yaml-like metadata
---

# Heading syntax (h1–h6)
::: note / warning / theorem / definition :::
$inline math$  and  $$display math$$
@fig{path}{caption}  @ref{label}  @cite{key}
| table | rows |
*bold*, _italic_, `code`
```

### Assembly (.ltasm)
Three-address IR with labels, typed operations, and register allocation hints.



The `bootstrap/` directory contains LATERALUS source that implements
the compiler itself:

```
bootstrap/
    v2_lexer.ltl     -- Tokenizer in LATERALUS
    v2_parser.ltl    -- Parser in LATERALUS
    v2_codegen.ltl   -- Code generator in LATERALUS
```

The self-hosting plan:
1. v1.3 compiler compiles the v2 bootstrap sources
2. v2 bootstrap becomes a minimal LATERALUS compiler
3. v2 compiler compiles itself (bootstrapping complete)
4. v2 replaces v1 as the primary compiler

## Directory Structure

```
lateralus-lang/
    lateralus_lang/     -- Python implementation
        __init__.py         -- Version, exports
        __main__.py         -- CLI entry point (26+ subcommands)
        lexer.py            -- Tokenizer (123 token types)
        parser.py           -- Recursive-descent parser (1,756 lines)
        ast_nodes.py        -- AST definitions (106 node types)
        compiler.py         -- Pipeline orchestrator
        ir.py               -- IR + semantic analysis
        codegen/
            python.py       -- Python 3.10+ transpiler
            c_backend.py    -- C99 transpiler (hosted + freestanding)
            js_backend.py   -- JavaScript (ES2020) transpiler
            wasm_backend.py -- WebAssembly text format transpiler
        vm/
            vm.py           -- Stack-based VM (102 opcodes)
            disassembler.py -- Bytecode disassembler (v2.4)
        math_engine.py      -- Mathematical computing
        crypto_engine.py    -- Cryptography
        science.py          -- Scientific computing
        markup.py           -- LTLML parser + HTML renderer
        bytecode_format.py  -- Binary format (.ltlc)
        error_engine.py     -- Rich diagnostics with suggestions
        engines.py          -- Unified engine interface
        optimizer.py        -- 10 optimization passes (O0-O3)
        type_system.py      -- HM type inference + checker
        async_runtime.py    -- Concurrency
        repl_enhanced.py    -- Interactive REPL (14 commands)
        lsp_server.py       -- Language server (JSON-RPC 2.0)
        dap_server.py       -- Debug Adapter Protocol server
        formatter.py        -- Code formatter
        linter.py           -- Code linter (21+ rules)
        debugger.py         -- Interactive debugger
        package_manager.py  -- Package management
        bench.py            -- Micro-benchmarks
        test_runner.py      -- .ltl test runner
        integration_patch.py -- Engine integration
        cli_extensions.py   -- Extended CLI
    stdlib/              -- Standard library (59 modules)
    tests/               -- Test suites (43 files, 1,976 tests)
    bootstrap/           -- Self-hosting compiler
    vscode-lateralus/    -- VS Code extension
    lateralus-os/        -- LateralusOS bare-metal kernel
    docs/                -- Documentation (.ltlml)
    examples/            -- Example programs (38 .ltl files)
    scripts/             -- Build & maintenance scripts
```

